"Info.dedicationHeading" = "Dedication";

"Info.dedicationText" = "David Compton was my high-school Nordic-skiing coach. He was also a French teacher but not initially ~my~ French teacher. He was aware of my interest in and aptitude for French, however. At the beginning of my junior year, I wasnâ€™t going to be able to take French because of a schedule conflict with Advanced Placement English. So Mr. Compton created a five-days-a-week French-literature class just for me. A German exchange student named Julian Peters soon joined us. Using Volumes I and II of â€œAnthologie de la LittÃ©rature FranÃ§aiseâ€ by Robert Leggewie as our textbooks, we studied the greats of French literature from ChrÃ©tien de Troyes to Samuel Beckett. This literary study ultimately inspired ~Conjuguer~â€™s use of literary examples of tense use. I thoroughly enjoyed Mr Comptonâ€™s class, and my knowledge of French took a giant leap. At the end of the year, I achieved a maximum score on the French Advanced Placement test. At the beginning of my freshman year at Dartmouth College, I took a test to get credit for a major-level French class and, of the sixty freshmen who took the test, I was one of only three who passed.

Mr. Compton already had a full class schedule in the fall of 1991, when he created the class for me. On some level, he might have enjoyed spending that class period puffing on his tobacco pipe, tinkering with his Macintosh computer. Solipsistic teen that I was, I never asked him ~why~ he sacrificed that time for me. But I can speculate. He studied at the Sorbonne during the 1960s and was a francophile. He may have recognized in me a shared interest in French and wanted to give me the opportunity to pursue it to the fullest extent possible. Whatever his motivation, I am grateful and dedicate this app to him.

Thanks to Mr. Compton, the name of ~Conjuguer~ is correctly spelled. During my freshman year at Dartmouth College, I developed the predecessor to ~Conjuguer~, ~Le Conjugateur~, a HyperCard stack. During a break from school, I demonstrated ~Le Conjugateur~ to Mr. Compton. He was impressed but commented that I was consistently misspelling the French word for â€œconjugateâ€, â€œconjuguerâ€, as â€œconjugerâ€. A rapid correction ensued and endured.";

