"Info.terminologyHeading" = "Terminology";

"Info.terminologyText" = "`Verb`

A ~verb~ is a kind of word that describes an action. For example, in the sentence â€œJacques Brel played the guitarâ€, â€œplayâ€ is the verb. Likewise, in the sentence â€œJacques Brel jouait de la guitareâ€, â€œjouerâ€ is the verb. Verb ~tense~s express, among other things, when an action took, takes, or will take place. In the example sentences, the verb tenses indicate that the action (playing the guitar) took place in the past. In English and in French, the ~subject~ or actor in the sentence, combined with the tense, determine the form of the verb used. This is the verb ~conjugation~. In English, the example sentenceâ€™s combination of subject and tense results in the conjugation â€œplayedâ€. In French, the conjugation is â€œjouaitâ€.

The ~infinitif~ (infinitive) is an invariant verb form that usually ends in -er, -ir, or -re. Unlike a conjugation, an ~infinitif~ does not indicate time, number, or person. Example use: â€œJacques Brel savait ~chanter~.â€ = â€œJacques Brel $knEw$ how ~to sing~.â€ In both sentences, the infinitif represents the ~act~ of singing without reference to time, number, or person.

French dictionaries and ~Conjuguer~â€™s Verbs tab list infinitif forms of verbs.

The ~radical de lâ€™infinitif~ (infinitive stem) is the infinitif minus its -er, -ir, or -re ending. This stem is the base for most conjugations.

`Pronoun`

A subject ~pronoun~ is a word that stands in for the subject in a sentence. The subject is the actor. In English, the subject pronouns in widespread use are ~I~, ~you~, ~he/she/it/one~, ~we~, ~you/yâ€™all~, and ~they~. The English subject pronouns ~ye~ and ~thou~ have been in decline since the Elizabethan period.

Subject pronouns correspond to the ~singular~ or ~plural~ number and to the ~first person~, ~second person~, or ~third person~. English subject pronouns follow. Abbreviations of the person-number combinations are in parentheses.

first person, singular (1s): ~I~
second person, singular (2s): ~you~
third person, singular (3s): ~he/she/it/one~
first person, plural (1p): ~we~
second person, plural (2p): ~you/yâ€™all~
third person, plural (3p): ~they~

Except with respect to 2s, the choice of subject pronoun in French is straightforward.

1s: ~je~
3s: ~il~ (masc.)/~elle~ (fem.)/~on~
1p: ~nous~
2p: ~vous~
3p: ~ils~ (masc.)/~elles~ (fem.)

â€œFem.â€ means that a pronoun refers to female subjects, and â€œmasc.â€ means that a pronoun refers to male subjects.

In quotidian speech, â€œonâ€ replaces â€œnousâ€ and uses 3s conjugations.

With respect to 2s, there are two choices: ~tu~ and ~vous~. ~Tu~ and its conjugations express intimacy, familiarity, friendliness, or, when used in anger on a stranger, rudeness. ~Vous~ and its conjugations express politeness, respect, or, when used on a former intimate, desire for emotional distance.

`Order of Presentation of Conjugations`

Treatises on French verbs, when presenting the conjugations for a particular tense, use the following person-number order: 1s, 2s, 3s, 1p, 2p, 3p. Respecting tradition, ~Conjuguer~ does the same. For example, ~Conjuguer~ would present the indicatif-prÃ©sent conjugations of ~Ãªtre~ as follows:

$SUIs$, $Es$, $ESt$, $SOMMEs$, $ÃªteS$, $SOnt$

Red letters in conjugations represent irregularities. A verb is considered irregular if any of its conjugations differs from the conjugation of a regular ~er~, ~ir~, or ~re~ verb.";

"Info.irregularitiesHeading" = "Irregularities";

"Info.irregularitiesText" = "Of the 6,314 verbs in ~Conjuguer~, 5,217 have conjugations that are completely regular. A completely regular conjugation uses the radical de lâ€™infinitif as its stem, and the ending is completely predictable. These are verbs that are conjugated using verb models 1-1 (regular -er), 2-1 (regular -ir), and 5-1A (regular -re). Examples:

cacaber -> vous cacabÃ¢tes
alunir -> nous alunissons
Ã©pandre -> Ã©pandu

The other 1,097 verbs are conjugated using one of ninety-two irregular-verb models. Verb models exhibit irregularities in three ways.

First, the stem used differs from the radical de lâ€™infinitif, but the ending is predictable. Example:

suivre -> je $suIs$ (~not~ suivs)

Second, the stem is as expected, but the ending is unpredictable. Example:

Ãªtre -> vous $ÃªteS$ (~not~ Ãªtez)

Third, both the stem ~and~ ending are unpredictable. Example:

aller -> elles $VOnt$ (~not~ allent)

~Conjuguer~ represents stem alterations and unpredictable endings for verb models in the following manner:

