"Info.defectivenessHeading" = "Defectiveness";

"Info.defectivenessText" = "`Types`

Sixty-five French verbs are ~defective~. This doesnâ€™t mean that something is wrong with them. No, defective in this context means that these verbs lack certain or even all conjugations. Verbs may be considered defective for a variety of reasons.

1. Use of certain person-numbers would be non-sensical. For example, â€œje $faUX$ que tu restesâ€ would ~literally~ mean â€œI $AM$ necessary that you stayâ€. %Falloir% is therefore defective for all person-numbers except 3s. â€œIl $faUt$ que tu restesâ€ makes sense, meaning â€œit $IS$ necessary that you stayâ€.

2. Some verbs are impersonal. This doesnâ€™t mean that they lack that human touch. No, impersonal in this context means that their subject is, in English, generic â€œitâ€ or, in French, generic â€œilâ€. These verbs involve natural phenomena like snow, hail, sleet, and rain. â€œIl $pleuT$.â€ = â€œIt is raining.â€ Because of the customary â€œilâ€ subjects, these verbs are considered defective for person-numbers other than 3s. There is, however, ~some~ flexibility. Quoting and translating Voltaire, â€œLes calomnies pleuvent sur quiconque rÃ©ussit.â€ = â€œCalumnies rain on whoever succeeds.â€ One could imagine other person-numbers being used for impersonal verbs in poetry. For example, in a poem written from the perspective of nature, the pronoun and conjugation â€œje neigeâ€, meaning â€œI $AM$ snowingâ€, would make sense.

3. Some verbs are defective in certain tenses in order to avoid confusion with other verbsâ€™ conjugations. For example, %paÃ®tre% is defective in the %passÃ© simple% because the conjugations suggested by analogy with %connaÃ®tre%, $Pus$, $Pus$, $Put$, $PÃ»mes$, $PÃ»tes$, and $Purent$, are identical to %pouvoir%â€™s passÃ©-simple conjugations.

4. Some verbs are defective because they have fallen out of use except in certain fixed expressions. %OuÃ¯r (trad.)% (to hear or listen) has been replaced by %entendre% and %Ã©couter% except in the expressions â€œoui-direâ€ = â€œhearsayâ€ and â€œO$Yez$!â€ = â€œListen!â€ (addressing Parliament). %Ester% (to be or stay) has been replaced by %Ãªtre% and %rester% except in the expression â€œester en justiceâ€ = â€œbe a party in legal proceedingsâ€. %GÃ©sir% (to lie prone) ~is~ still occasionally used in the %indicatif prÃ©sent% and %imparfait%, but the ~primary~ use of this verb is â€œci-$gÃt$â€ = â€œhere lies (dead)â€, a common tombstone inscription.

`Reasons for Inclusion`

Reference works on French verbs, for example the book â€œFrench Verbs Made Simple(r)â€ and the website Wiktionary, omit defective conjugations entirely. But the developer of ~Conjuguer~ is providing ~all~ conjugations, including those traditionally considered defective, to you, the user of this app. Three reasons for this heterodox generosity follow.

1. As stated in â€œFrench Verbs Made Simple(r)â€, â€œThere is occasionally disagreement [among] various sources as to which [conjugations] actually exist.â€ Similarly, regarding the word %ravoir%, Wiktionary says, â€œDâ€™aprÃ¨s la plupart des dictionnaires classiques, ce verbe $EST$ dÃ©fectif et ne se conjugue pas. NÃ©anmoins, des usages de formes conjuguÃ©es $SONT$ avÃ©rÃ©es rÃ©gionalement.â€ To omit certain conjugations, therefore, would require a series of judgment calls by the developer of ~Conjuguer~. He judgeth not lest he be judged.

2. Certain conjugations are likely absent from any large corpus of French text and could therefore be considered defective. But the fact that a conjugation $Is$nâ€™t used doesnâ€™t mean that it couldnâ€™t be useful. Consider a poem written from the perspective of the clouds of Earth and Venus. This poem might include the line â€œWe rain water and sulphuric acid, respectively.â€ Thus, although pleuvoir is considered defective for 1p in all conjugated tenses, this conjugation (pleuvons) would be useful in such a poem.

3. %Ester% (to be or stay), though nearly extinct in French, has heavily used relatives in other Romance languages. For example, Spanish has two words for â€œto beâ€: â€œserâ€ and (you guessed it) â€œestarâ€. ~Conjuguer~â€™s users might be curious how esterâ€™s conjugations would have evolved had that verb remained productive in French, as it did in Spanish. Similarly, ~Conjuguer~â€™s users might also be curious how %clore%â€™s conjugations would have evolved had %fermer% not replaced it. For the benefit of curious users, ~Conjuguer~ includes speculative conjugations of %choir%, %clore%, %ester%, %gÃ©sir%, %issir%, and %ouÃ¯r%, inspired by the Old French conjugations provided by Wiktionary and â€œTableaux de conjugaison de lâ€™ancien franÃ§aisâ€ by Machio Okada and Hitoshi Ogurisu.

Notwithstanding ~Conjuguer~â€™s inclusive approach to conjugations traditionally considered defective, those conjugations ~are~ called out with strikethrough in ~Conjuguer~â€™s user interface.";

